), journalist and politician from Nova Scotia, Canada. He opposed the 1864 Quebec Resolutions for confederation of the Canadian provinces, arguing that the proposed bill would lead to the political and economic ruin of Nova Scotia; he headed the delegation to London to lobby against the plan, July 1866–May 1867. His campaign failed; the British North America Act was passed, 1867, resulting in the unification of Canada, and the Canadian United Parliament met for the first time in Ottawa, 7 Nov. 1867.

