Carlyle, John Aitken (Jack, “The Doctor”) (1801–79; ODNB
), TC’s brother, physician, and translator. He m., 1852, Phoebe Elizabeth Hough Watt, b. Fowler (1810–54), wealthy widow of Fitzjames Watt (1809–48), from Leek in Staffordshire, with four sons; she d. in childbirth; the child was stillborn. John A. Carlyle assumed responsibility for his stepsons: Thomas Fowler (1838–62), went to sea in 1856 (see 32:29TC to IC, 12 Nov. 1856
), went to Australia, 1861, and d. on his return (see 
38:115TC to JWC, 2 July 1862); Henry (b. 1839), at sea from 1854 (see 
29:121TC to JCA, 30 June 1854), m., 1863, Jane Wilson, b. Hunter (1837–1908), da. of John A. Carlyle’s friend John Hunter (1801–69; see 
8:161JWC to SS, [June or July? 1835]) and of Helen, b. Vary (1804–85); Arthur (b. 1840), joined the civil service 1862; and William (b. 1842), an officer in the Dragoons; he m., 18 July 1867, Mary Smith, da. of E. H. Smith of Grouville, Jersey.

Chapman, Frederic (1823–95; 
ODNB
), partner in Chapman   Hall; took over the management of the company 1864; he m., 1861, Clara, b. Woodin (1842–28 Feb. 1867); they had one surviving son, Frederic, and a baby who d. early 1867.

Chorley, John Rutter (1806–29 June 1867; ODNB ; see 19:135 TC to JWC, [early Aug. 1845] , and 22:30 TC to JAC, 8 Aug. 1847
), poet and scholar of Spanish literature, reviewer for the Athenaeum; highly regarded by TC. He helped supervise the building of the soundproof room in the attic of 5 Cheyne Row in 1853 (see 28:245 TC to JCA, 11 Aug. 1853
, and Carlyle, Reminiscences 154) and assisted in proofreading Frederick (see 34:146 TC to HL, 18 Aug. 1858
). He lived at 76 Chester Sq., Pimlico.

