Maccall, William (1812–88; 
ODNB
), impoverished writer, Unitarian preacher, lecturer, and author; m., 1842, Alice, b. Haselden (1813–78); they had one da., Elizabeth (b. 1843). They lived at Fountain Villa, Woolwich Rd., Bexley Heath, Kent. See K. J. Fielding, “Carlyle, Charles Dickens, and William Maccall,” Notes and Queries n.s. 1 (1954): 488–90.

Masson, David (1822–1907; 
ODNB
; see 
16:312JWC to TC, [24 July 1843]
); writer and editor, prof. of English lang. and lit., University Coll., London, 1853–65, and of rhetoric and English lit., Edinburgh Univ., 1865–95. He m., 1853, Emily Rosaline, b. Orme (1835–1915); they had four children; they lived at 3 Roseberry Terr., Edinburgh. He was also ed. of Macmillan’s Magazine
1859–68.

Mill, John Stuart (1806–73; 
ODNB), utilitarian philosopher and economist; m., 1851, Harriet Taylor, b. Hardy (1807–58; 
ODNB
), who strongly influenced his thinking. Mill met TC in Sept. 1831 (see 
5:398TC to JWC, 4 Sept. 1831); they remained on friendly terms even after the MS of vol. 1 of The French Revolution was burned while in Mill’s keeping (see 
8:66-68
TC to JFR, 7 March 1835), but later they became estranged because of many differences in temperament and attitudes to social questions; Mill also believed that TC and other friends disapproved of his marriage. Elected Liberal M.P. for Westminster 1865.

Ruskin, John (1819–1900; 
ODNB), author, artist, and social reformer; m., 1848, Euphemia Chalmers, b. Gray (1828–97); marriage annulled 1854 (she then m., 1855, John Everett Millais [1829–96; 
ODNB], artist). Ruskin lived in the family home at 163 Denmark Hill, S London, with his mother, Margaret, b. Cock (1781–1871). His father, John James Ruskin (1785–1864), was a wine merchant. Ruskin was J. M. W. Turner’s foremost admirer and was strongly influenced by TC.

